# Git sync — Mac (agent) ↔ GitHub ↔ Windows (build + print-test)

This repo is edited on **macOS** (agent). Windows work uses **two machines**:

| Machine | Git / build | Physical prints |
|---|---|---|
| **Build VM** (Windows VM on Mac) | Yes — pull, publish, zip | No printer |
| **Print-test PC** (physical box) | No — receives zip only | Yes — staging sign-off |

GitHub is the handoff from Mac to the **build VM**. The **print-test PC** gets `artifacts\app` as a zip — never `git pull`.

**Default branch for active work:** check `git branch` on the build VM (e.g. `bug-fixes`, `feature/sprint-1-m1`).

---

## Agent — when to commit and push

### MUST commit + push (same session, no need to ask)

- Any change under `src/EventPlatform.PrintRelay.App/` or `src/EventPlatform.PrintRelay.Spike/` the user will run on Windows
- Bug fixes reported from Windows testing
- User says **commit**, **push**, or **commit and push**
- Story work marked Done that includes runnable app behaviour

Use one commit per logical fix/feature. Message: what/why (not a file list).

### MUST NOT commit or push unless the user asks

- Read-only answers, plans, or investigations with **no code changes**
- User says **don't commit** or **don't push**
- Partial/WIP that does not meet story acceptance (unless user explicitly wants a WIP push)

### After every push — tell the user in the reply

1. **Branch:** e.g. `feature/sprint-1-m1`
2. **Commit:** short SHA + subject line, e.g. `cb22916 Fix tray startup deadlock…`
3. **Reminder:** Build VM sync is **one step at a time** — first reply gives pull only; wait for operator report before publish/zip (see `windows-operator-steps.mdc`). Physical prints happen on the **print-test PC** after zip transfer.

Core-only / tests / docs-only changes: push is optional; say **“Not pushed — Windows exe unchanged”** or push if bundled with App changes in the same session.

---

## Build VM — sync and publish before every test

Run in **PowerShell** on the **build VM** (`C:\Users\Deon\event-platform-print-relay-windows` or your clone path).

### 1. Pull latest (required after agent says it pushed)

```powershell
cd C:\Users\Deon\event-platform-print-relay-windows
git fetch origin
git checkout <branch-agent-gave-you>
git pull origin <branch-agent-gave-you>
git log -1 --oneline
```

**Check:** `git log -1` matches the commit SHA/subject the agent gave you. If not, you are not on the right branch or pull failed.

### 2. Stop the old app (required before publish)

```powershell
taskkill /IM EventPlatform.PrintRelay.exe /F
```

### 3. Publish

```powershell
dotnet publish src\EventPlatform.PrintRelay.App -c Release -r win-x64 --self-contained -o artifacts\app
```

Publish must end with `-> ...\artifacts\app\` and **no** `MSB3027` file-lock errors.

**ARM64 Windows (Surface / Snapdragon laptops):** always pass **`-r win-x64`** as above. If you omit `-r`, `dotnet publish` defaults to `win-arm64` and Pdfium may fail with *“Native Library not found … win-arm64\native\pdfium.dll”*. After publish, confirm Pdfium is present (any one may be true):

```powershell
@(
  ".\artifacts\app\runtimes\win-x64\native\pdfium.dll",
  ".\artifacts\app\x64\pdfium.dll",
  ".\artifacts\app\pdfium.dll"
) | ForEach-Object { if (Test-Path $_) { "OK $_" } }
```

At least one line must print `OK …`. If none do, the publish did not bundle Pdfium — pull latest and republish.

### 4. Verify build (safe — no dialog)

**Do not rely on `--version` in PowerShell** — `EventPlatform.PrintRelay.App` is `OutputType` **WinExe** (GUI subsystem). `Console.WriteLine` in `--version` has no attached console, so PowerShell often shows **no output** even when the exe exits 0. This is expected; not a failed build.

Use these instead:

```powershell
Get-Content .\artifacts\app\build-info.txt
(Get-Item .\artifacts\app\EventPlatform.PrintRelay.exe).VersionInfo.FileVersion
```

Optional (may still be blank in PowerShell):

```powershell
.\artifacts\app\EventPlatform.PrintRelay.exe --version
```

Avoid **`--about`** unless troubleshooting UI (shows a dialog).

### 5. Zip for print-test PC

```powershell
Compress-Archive -Path artifacts\app\* -DestinationPath artifacts\print-relay-build.zip -Force
```

Copy `artifacts\print-relay-build.zip` to the print-test PC (USB, cloud, or network share). On the print-test PC, extract to a fixed folder (e.g. `C:\PrintRelay`) and run the `.exe` from there.

---

## Print-test PC — run transferred build (no git)

The print-test PC does **not** clone the repo or run `dotnet publish`. It only runs the extracted publish output.

### 1. Extract (first time or after each new zip)

```powershell
Expand-Archive -Path .\print-relay-build.zip -DestinationPath C:\PrintRelay -Force
```

Adjust paths if your zip lands elsewhere.

### 2. Stop old relay before replacing files

```powershell
taskkill /IM EventPlatform.PrintRelay.exe /F
```

Then extract again (overwrites files in `C:\PrintRelay`).

### 3. Verify build matches build VM

**Do not rely on `--version` in PowerShell** — WinExe has no console; output is often blank. Use:

```powershell
Get-Content C:\PrintRelay\build-info.txt
(Get-Item C:\PrintRelay\EventPlatform.PrintRelay.exe).VersionInfo.FileVersion
```

Compare `build-info.txt` commit SHA to what the agent reported from the build VM.

### 4. Run

```powershell
C:\PrintRelay\EventPlatform.PrintRelay.exe
```

Always launch the **`.exe`** directly — do **not** use `dotnet EventPlatform.PrintRelay.dll`.

Tray icon may be under the **^** overflow by the clock.

Physical print sign-off (staging walk-in, designer compare, `relay.log`) happens **only** on the print-test PC.

